		<paragraph type="text" x="12" y="+0" width="407" height="0" style="normal" tabs="" indent="0"><![CDATA[<TEXTFORMAT LEADING="2"><P ALIGN="LEFT"><FONT FACE="Verdana" SIZE="13" COLOR="#000000" LETTERSPACING="0" KERNING="0">The chart shows that the world's population [3] at a rapid pace over the last two centuries. [4] 1804 there were 1 billion people in the world. By 1927, 123 years later, the population [5]. Remarkably, it only took another [6] years for the population to double once again. By the turn of the millennium, the population had risen [7] another 2.1 billion. If this upward trend continues, it is predicted that by 2050 the number of people sharing the planet [8] to just over 9 billion.</FONT></P></TEXTFORMAT>]]></paragraph>
		<paragraph type="text" x="12" y="+0" width="407" height="0" style="normal" tabs="" indent="0"><![CDATA[<TEXTFORMAT LEADING="2"><P ALIGN="LEFT">&nbsp;</P></TEXTFORMAT>]]></paragraph>
		<paragraph type="text" x="12" y="+0" width="407" height="0" style="normal" tabs="" indent="0"><![CDATA[<TEXTFORMAT LEADING="2"><P ALIGN="LEFT"><FONT FACE="Verdana" SIZE="13" COLOR="#000000" LETTERSPACING="0" KERNING="0">As regards how the global population is distributed, the table shows that less developed regions account for by far the greatest proportion of people in the world. It also reveals that regional population trends are expected to vary considerably. Large population [9] are projected for less developed regions, particularly for the least developed [10] within them. By 2050 the population of the former will have increased by just under [11], while that of the latter will have almost [12]. In sharp contrast, the population of more developed regions is expected to [13] slightly. As a result, the [14] billion people living in less developed regions in 2050 will account for almost 9 out of every 10 people on earth.</FONT></P></TEXTFORMAT>]]></paragraph>
		<paragraph type="text" x="12" y="+0" width="407" height="0" style="normal" tabs="" indent="0"><![CDATA[<TEXTFORMAT LEADING="2"><P ALIGN="LEFT">&nbsp;</P></TEXTFORMAT>]]></paragraph>
